All analyses were performed using IBM SPSS Statistics software (IBM, Armonk, NY, USA) and the PROCESS macro [44, 45] . Mann-Whitney U tests were performed to examine group differences in demographic control variables. Four separate moderation regression analyses were performed to examine whether sex and diagnosis moderated main effects of amyloid status on RAVLT learning and delayed free recall scores as well as left and right HVs. For all analyses, we treated A + as an independent variable, diagnosis as a moderator, and sex as a secondary moderator. Modified MoCA scores, age at screening visit, education, and APOE ε4 carrier status were included as covariates. All continuous covariates were mean-centered; dichotomous covariates were zerocentered.
